# Choosing Ports to Scan

## Scan Every Port

```bash
nmap -p- 10.10.10.5
```

Scans all **65535** TCP ports.

Useful when you don't want to miss anything.

---

## Scan Well-Known Ports

```bash
nmap -p1-1023 10.10.10.5
```

Scans ports **1 through 1023**.

This covers most common services.

---

## Scan Specific Ports

```bash
nmap -p22,80,443 10.10.10.5
```

Only scans the ports you specify.

Example:

```
22/tcp   open   ssh
80/tcp   open   http
443/tcp  open   https
```

---

## Fast Scan

```bash
nmap -F 10.10.10.5
```

Scans only the **100 most common ports**.

Great for quick reconnaissance.

---

## Scan Ports Sequentially

```bash
nmap -r 10.10.10.5
```

Normally Nmap randomizes the order of ports.

The `-r` option scans them in numerical order.

---

# Controlling Scan Speed

Sometimes scanning as fast as possible isn't always the best choice.

Nmap lets you control how aggressive the scan should be.

## Timing Templates

Very slow

```bash
nmap -T0 target
```

Normal

```bash
nmap -T3 target
```

Very aggressive

```bash
nmap -T5 target
```

Higher timing values make scans faster but can also increase the chances of being detected or missing responses.

---

## Limit Scan Rate

Maximum 50 packets every second

```bash
nmap --max-rate 50 target
```

---

Minimum 15 packets every second

```bash
nmap --min-rate 15 target
```

---

## Increase Parallelism

```bash
nmap --min-parallelism 100 target
```

Allows Nmap to send many probes at the same time, making scans faster on stable networks.

---

# Commands Covered

| Option | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| `-sT` | TCP Connect Scan |
| `-sS` | TCP SYN (Stealth) Scan |
| `-sU` | UDP Scan |
| `-p-` | Scan all ports |
| `-p1-1023` | Scan ports 1 to 1023 |
| `-F` | Scan the 100 most common ports |
| `-r` | Scan ports in order |
| `-T0` to `-T5` | Control scan speed |
| `--max-rate` | Set maximum packet rate |
| `--min-rate` | Set minimum packet rate |
| `--min-parallelism` | Send multiple probes simultaneously |

